Here is the complete, detailed implementation plan.

## Detailed Implementation Plan

### Step 1: Add the `common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3()` function

**File**: `common/chat.cpp`
**Location**: Insert this new static function just before line 1634 (before `common_chat_try_specialized_template`). This follows the convention where all `common_chat_params_init_*` functions are defined above the dispatcher.

The function uses the `standard_json_tools` helper from `common_chat_peg_builder` to handle the Mistral v0.3 JSON-array tool call format. This is significantly cleaner than manually constructing PEG parser rules for JSON object fields.

**Function design**:

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
    const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
    const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;

    auto has_tools       = inputs.tools.is_array() && !inputs.tools.empty();
    auto include_grammar = true;

    data.prompt            = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format            = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE;
    data.supports_thinking = false;
    data.preserved_tokens  = {
        "[TOOL_CALLS]",
    };

    auto parser = build_chat_peg_parser([&](common_chat_peg_builder & p) {
        auto generation_prompt = p.prefix(inputs.generation_prompt);

        // JSON schema response format
        if (inputs.json_schema.is_object() && !inputs.json_schema.empty()) {
            return generation_prompt << p.content(
                p.schema(p.json(), "response-format", inputs.json_schema));
        }

        // Tool call parser
        // Format: [TOOL_CALLS][{"name": "func", "arguments": {...}, "id": "123456789"}, ...]
        if (has_tools && inputs.tool_choice != COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_NONE) {
            auto tool_calls = p.standard_json_tools(
                /* section_start      = */ "[TOOL_CALLS]",
                /* section_end        = */ "",
                /* tools              = */ inputs.tools,
                /* parallel_tool_calls = */ inputs.parallel_tool_calls,
                /* force_tool_calls   = */ inputs.tool_choice == COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_REQUIRED,
                /* name_key           = */ "name",
                /* args_key           = */ "arguments",
                /* array_wrapped      = */ true,
                /* function_is_key    = */ false,
                /* call_id_key        = */ "id",
                /* gen_call_id_key    = */ ""
            );

            return generation_prompt + (p.content(p.until("[TOOL_CALLS]")) << tool_calls);
        }

        // Content-only parser
        include_grammar = false;
        return generation_prompt << p.content(p.rest());
    });

    data.parser = parser.save();

    if (include_grammar) {
        data.grammar_lazy = has_tools && inputs.tool_choice == COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_AUTO;

        data.grammar = build_grammar([&](const common_grammar_builder & builder) {
            foreach_function(inputs.tools, [&](const json & tool) {
                const auto & function = tool.at("function");
                auto         schema   = function.at("parameters");
                builder.resolve_refs(schema);
            });
            parser.build_grammar(builder, data.grammar_lazy);
        });

        data.grammar_triggers = {
            { COMMON_GRAMMAR_TRIGGER_TYPE_WORD, "[TOOL_CALLS]" }
        };
    }

    return data;
}
```

**Key design points**:

1. **`standard_json_tools` usage**: This is the cleanest approach. The helper already handles JSON array wrapping (`array_wrapped = true`), field names (`name_key = "name"`, `args_key = "arguments"`), and call IDs (`call_id_key = "id"`). It builds the correct PEG parser rules internally.

2. **No reasoning support**: `supports_thinking = false`. No `[THINK]`/`[/THINK]` handling. The Mistral v0.3 format has no reasoning markers.

3. **Grammar trigger**: `[TOOL_CALLS]` triggers grammar-constrained generation when tools are available in `AUTO` mode (lazy grammar).

4. **JSON schema support**: When `json_schema` is provided, the parser constrains generation to the schema (same pattern as other handlers).

5. **Preserved tokens**: `[TOOL_CALLS]` must be preserved so the tokenizer does not split it into sub-tokens.

### Step 2: Add detection logic in `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`

**File**: `common/chat.cpp`
**Location**: Add a new `if` block inside `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`, after the Ministral 3 check (after line 1644) and before the GPT-OSS check (before line 1646).

**Detection code**:

```cpp
    // Mistral Instruct v0.3 - uses [INST]/[/INST] with inline system messages (no [SYSTEM_PROMPT])
    // Tool calls use JSON array format: [TOOL_CALLS][{"name": ..., "arguments": ..., "id": ...}]
    if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[ARGS]") == std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[CALL_ID]") == std::string::npos) {
        LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v3\n");
        return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
    }
```

**Why this placement**:
- Must come **after** the Ministral 3 check because both look at `[INST]`-family markers. The Ministral 3 check is more specific (requires `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` AND `[TOOL_CALLS]` AND `[ARGS]`), so it will match first for templates that have all those. But to be safe and explicit, our check requires absence of `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`, `[ARGS]`, and `[CALL_ID]`.
- Comes **before** unrelated handlers (GPT-OSS, Functionary, etc.) for logical grouping.

**Detection rationale**:
| Condition | Purpose |
